data.title: MENTOR Greater Milwaukee Staff
data.meta_description: Meet the members of the MENTOR Greater Milwaukee staff who assist in providing quality mentoring experiences for young people.
data.text:
Gaulien Smith

Owner, Gee’s Clippers

Board Chair, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Gaulien “Gee” Smith opened the doors of Gee’s Clippers on June 1, 1995 with just 4 barbers and himself. Today Gee’s Clippers has grown to a 30 chair barbershop, and undoubtedly the leading barbershop in the state of Wisconsin. Gee and his staff has been the barber or stylist to hundreds of professional athletes, politicians and celebrities over the past 26 years.

Gee’s Clippers is making strides like no other barbershop in history. Gaulien has created community partnerships with the Milwaukee Bucks and numerous other large companies in the Milwaukee area. He also has a health clinic in his barbershop called Gee’s MKE Wellness Clinic. Providing health care and awareness to individuals in the community.

Gee and Gee’s Clippers are most known and respected because of their relentless commitment to the community. Giving of their time, money and resources, such as toy drives, coat drives, feeding families in need, creating a safe place and platform for men to talk about challenges they face and mental health which is an area that Gaulien is passionate about. Gee’s Clippers have received many awards and recognitions for their great work in the city of Milwaukee and across the globe.

Amanda Braun

Director of Athletics, University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee

Board Member, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Amanda Braun is in her eighth year as the Director of Athletics at the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee. The first-ever female to hold the post at Milwaukee, she was named to the position in March of 2013 before officially taking the reins of the department on May 1, 2013. In her tenure on campus, she has helped Milwaukee to new heights, starting by playing the lead role in bringing Panther men’s basketball contests back downtown. She also was instrumental in helping the University secure naming rights for UW-Milwaukee Panther Arena.

The department also received its first-ever $1 million gift under Braun’s watch in Fall of 2016, the largest ever made to Milwaukee Athletics at the time. A former basketball player at Siena College, Braun graduated summa cum laude with a degree in psychology and later earned a master’s in sports administration from the University of North Carolina. Braun is married to Kelly Braun and resides in Whitefish Bay.

Katina Shaw

Vice President of Community Relations and Family Liaison, Milwaukee Brewers

Board Member, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Katina Shaw is entering her 15th season with the Milwaukee Brewers Baseball Club. Her current position is Vice President of Community Relations and Family Liaison. Katina serves as the key liaison between the front office, players, their families, team ownership, investors and the community. She performs a variety of duties; including the creation and management of community programs, such as “Beyond the Diamond” Brewers monthly community volunteer outreach initiative, in addition to coordinating activities and programs for Brewers Wives, alumni and front office personnel, she also supports the community efforts of Brewers Community Foundation, the charitable arm of the Brewers.

Before joining the Brewers, Katina spent 8+ years in fundraising as the Market Manager for the Milwaukee Chapter of the American Diabetes Association, where she coordinated the fundraising efforts for the ADA Step Out Walk to Fight Diabetes in Milwaukee, Green Bay and Racine.

In June 2019, Shaw received The Business Journal Women of Influence Award and in February 2012, she received the Milwaukee Times Black Excellence Award, an honor that recognizes individuals who are making a positive difference in the community.

A native of Milwaukee, Katina resides in Milwaukee County with her husband Jermaine, son Jamar, grandson Jeremiah and their four-legged terrier, Tank. Katina is an active volunteer in the community, a member on various committees and serve on boards in the Milwaukee community such as; Girls Scouts of Wisconsin Southeastern, Make-A-Wish Wisconsin, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee, and Wisconsin Humane Society.

Nicole Brookshire

CEO, Brookshire Customized Solutions, LLC.

Board Member, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Nicole Brookshire is a Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion Chief Strategist with over twenty-years of experience in driving enterprise-wide transformational change, targeting social and programmatic impact across communities. Nicole is the CEO for Brookshire Customized Solutions, LLC. Mrs. Brookshire is currently supporting local planning projects with health advocacy groups and small business owners. Prior to expanding her consulting agency, Mrs. Brookshire was the Inaugural Executive Director for Milwaukee County’s Office on African American Affairs, a local jurisdiction, where her leadership served as the County’s catalyst to being the first in the nation to declare Racism as a Public Health Crisis and to develop a local county ordinance to institutionalize racial equity within the government structure. She also worked for three years at Junior Achievement of Wisconsin, as the Vice President of Operations, where she oversaw statewide district operations -growing education programs and partnerships. Nicole earned a Master’s Business of Administration degree from the University of Phoenix.

Jerry Roberts

Executive Director of the Milwaukee Area Workforce Funding Alliance

Board Member, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Jerry Roberts currently serves as Director of Philanthropic and Corporate Engagement for Midwest Urban Strategies, a consortium of 13 U.S. Department of Labor Workforce Development Boards working to marry traditional workforce development practices with economic development.

Jerry brings a career steeped in the corporate, nonprofit and philanthropy sectors. Roberts cultivates and leverages relationships with business partners and national leaders to assist in the development of strong regional workforce and economic initiatives. Previously, Jerry worked for Bader Philanthropies where he guided the Foundation’s annual $1.5 million investment in workforce grants and its growing $16 million Program Related Investment portfolio. Jerry’s contributions to the nonprofit sector include helping workforce development organizations move from their entrepreneurial beginnings to the next stage in organizational development and supporting conversations among regional leaders with an eye toward collaboration and systemic solutions.

Roberts also serves as the as the Executive Director of the Milwaukee Area Workforce Funding Alliance, a consortium of funders working on employment issues at the systemic level.

Jerry proudly serves on the board of Voice of the Experienced (VOTE), New Orleans and on the Race and Equity Advisory team of the National Fund for Workforce Solutions. He also lends his time, talent and resources to other boards and committees. Jerry is a 2016 Connecting Leaders Fellow of ABFE, the Association of Black Foundation Executives.

Roberts holds a master’s degree in the cultural foundations of education from the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee, as well as bachelor’s degrees from Grace Christian College and UW-Milwaukee.

Shane Arnold

Sr Staff, Enterprise Cloud & Data Platform Architect, GE Healthcare

Board Member, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Shane Arnold serves as the Sr Staff Infrastructure Cloud Architect at GE Healthcare. As the Cloud Infrastructure Architect, Shane is responsible for leading two teams of engineers and architects that design, support, and build GE Healthcare’s global enterprise data & analytics platform which enables organizational machine learning, data science and artificial intelligence development.

Shane is a Milwaukee Native who prior to his role at GE Healthcare, he has held various senior engineering and technology leadership roles at many of Milwaukee’s major companies which include, Johnson Controls, Northwestern Mutual, Miller Coors, and BMO Financial.

Shane has a deep passion and proven track record in mentorship, volunteerism, relationship cultivation and working with at-risk youth, in an effort to try to help connect people from underrepresented communities with information, direction, and opportunities.

Shane received a bachelor’s degree in psychology from The University of Kansas as well as a bachelor’s in information science and Technology from the University of Wisconsin – Milwaukee.

Terrell Walter

Executive Vice President, Royal Capital Group

Board Member, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Terrell Walter is a M.B.A. graduate of the University of Wisconsin- Whitewater with an emphasis in

Finance and Management, and an ACRE Alum. Joining Royal Capital Group in 2012, Terrell serves as Development Manager. In his role, Terrell leads the company’s project management, community engagement, entitlement, and construction management functions.

Prior to joining Royal Capital, Terrell spent three years in Finance as a registered representative providing investment guidance to individual and institutional investors. In this role, Terrell grew a passion for helping others and providing access to underrepresented people across all sectors.

Terrell’s commitment to the community is highlighted by his community and corporate affiliations

including:

• YMCA of Metropolitan Milwaukee (Board Member)

• Rite-Hite Family YMCA (Chair)

• City Year Milwaukee (Associate Board – Fundraising Committee Chair)

• MPS Black and Latino Male Achievement (Mentor)

• Mentor Greater Milwaukee (Board Member)

Awards and Recognitions:

• 40 Under 40 (Business Journal)

• Real Estate Change Agent (Business Journal)

Tiffany Davister

Partner – Indirect, State and Local Tax Services, Ernst & Young

Board Member, MENTOR Greater Milwaukee

Tiffany has 15+ years of tax experience. Serves as the Wisconsin State Desk for the EY Practice, Tiffany has significant experience in delivering state and international indirect tax work with a wide range of multinational clients. Prior to her current position with Ernst & Young, Tiffany serviced as an internal auditor for the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee. Tiffany is a CPA, licensed in Wisconsin. Tiffany has extensive income/franchise experience, including assisting with the Wisconsin State Desk for EY and Tiffany’s client service has focused on indirect aspects of multinational business from consulting to compliance, as well as experience in the daily functions of a tax department. Tiffany has strong relationships at the Department of Revenue, given her role serving as the Chair of the Wisconsin Taxation Committee, as well as her involvement with EY’s controversy practice, meeting regularly with Wisconsin Department of Revenue Auditors, Supervisors, and Section Chiefs/Directors. She has assisted various clients in the process of filing voluntary disclosures and meeting state tax filing requirements, as well as various controversy matters inside and outside Wisconsin. Tiffany has also worked on a variety of state income tax restructuring engagements throughout the Milwaukee area. She has extensive experience researching state tax issues, working through business and legal issues

related to corporate restructurings, and implementing tax saving strategies. Extensive experience performing lookback reviews of state tax filings for refunds and prospective favorable filing positions. More recently, Tiffany has assisted clients in looking at their current processes and creating connected tax functions, including implementing tax determination software, revamping existing processes and implementing ETR tools to create a more connected and efficient tax function. Tiffany advises clients on all facets of state income and franchise taxes and indirect taxes such as sales and use tax, property tax, employment tax, VAT and federal excise taxes.

Undergrad and Masters Degree in Public Accounting from University of Wisconsin – Milwaukee​
